On January 6, 2015, a Covenant Transport tractor trailer was involved in a rollover accident resulting the the release of an estimated 1,000 gallons of UN3082 Environmentally Hazardous Substance to the soil adjacent to the roadway. Seven totes on the trailer were damaged during the accident. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site for cleanup operations. The totes were removed from the overturned trailer and decontaminated. The totes were then loaded onto a replacement trailer to be transported to a nearby Covenant terminal. The totes were then transported to a secondary environmental contractor to be tested and the product was transferred into replacement containers.

column168: On January 8, 2015, during the examination of export documents offered for transport. The carrier (Seaboard Marine) noticed on an invoice that container SMLU256035-7 was carrying non-hazardous as well as hazardous cargo (UN 3163, Liquified Gas, N.O.S). The container was on terminal grounds at the time we (Seaboard Marine) notice that undeclared hazardous cargoes had been loaded. We immediately placed a HOLD on the container and prohibited future movement. The shipper was asked to provide the proper documentation describing all the hazardous materials inside of the container. The same day, upon receipt, review and acceptance of the shipping papers, the container was placarded accordingly and afterward released for transportation

A Clean Harbors employee was loading containers into a van trailer.  During this process the employee had to load a tote tank.  To save space on the trailer, the employee stage the tote side ways on the forks of fork lift.  As the employee approached the containers staged in the trailer, the forks of fork lift which extended beyond the tote, pierced the bottom of a staged drum causing the contents to release. The employee immediately layed the damaged drum on it's side to prevent further leakage. Additional employees contained and cleaned up the spill area inside the trailer.  The damaged drum along with all clean-up debris was placed inside a Salvage Drum and relased it for transportation to it's intended disposal facility.
column169: Employee was suspended operating a fork lift until he is re-trained on fork lift safe operations.  All other employees will receive a refresher course regarding this incident.

column168: On January 6, 2015, at 08:22 hours, Assistant Terminal Superintendent at the CSXT Willard Terminal, Willard, Ohio reported that a slow drip from TILX 280717 , a loaded tank car of UN1090, Acetone. Reportedly, there was product dripping from the bottom outlet valve. The tank car was placed on the spill containment pad in the Terminal and isolated. The shipper, Honeywell, was notified via Chemtrec, report #2015-01-06-00063 . Eagle Railcar, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Willard Terminal. Eagle Railcar found that the packing nut was improperly tightened on the bottom outlet valve. The packing nut was tightened appropriately and there was no further release. The shipper representative, Mark Swisher, 281-362-6705 was notified of the situation found. Honeywell is filing for a One Time Movement Approval prior to placing back into transportation. TILX 280717 is currently on hold pending the appropriate actions.  This incident did require a special move.  NARRI: 5x(5+3+0)x(2+0) = 80  Cause code:547

OOLU 850757 was carefully moved to the facility's containment area. Two damaged five gallon pails leaked commodity from abrasions and/or dents at their upper and/or bottom chimes.  Also noted were two one gallon sized jerricans that had leaked. The floor spillage inside OOLU 850757 was cleaned. All damaged packages were placed into an overpack drum and properly labeled.  All lading removed from OOLU 850757 was returned into the cleaned OOLU 850757 container, properly blocked and braced for continued transportation.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste at Clean Harbors Laurel MD facility was being loaded with intransit drums for continued transportation to the intended waste disposal facility. While doing the transfer the employee transferring the drum accidently punctured the side of a 55 gallon steel drum with the lower forks of his hand truck. The employee turned the drum upside down and stopped the leak and then put down absorbant pads and spill booms inside trailer. Employee contacted his supervisor and a crew over packed the drum and put all spill debris and PPE into an over pack for continued transportation to the drums intended disposal facility. The Maryland MDE was notified and chose not to respond Report # 1600-01162015

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: On January 16th, 2015 at 11:46 hours, personnel in the CSXT Frontier Yard discovered PPRX 660681, a loaded UN 1267, Petroleum Crude Oil tank car to have wetness down the sides of the tank car coming from around the manway. The car was isolated and the Shipper, Philadelphia Energy Solutions/Savage Services, was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2015-01-16-00119. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, EP+S of Vermont the Buffalo branch was dispatched to the scene, upon inspection it was determined that the release was from the manway cover due to swing bolts #2 + #3 where less than tool tight and #5 was over tightened, the manway cover was opened the gasket was inspected and found to have no defective issues. The nozzle, manway cover and tank car were wiped down and the cover was re-secured and tool tightened. Mr. Brendan Wright, with PES/Savage Services, office: 801-944-6558 was notified of the situation found and the corrective action taken. PPRX 660681 was released for transport. This incident did NOT require a special move.  Cause Code: 200 (5 points)  NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100
column169: Discussed with Savage Services personnel AAR Pamphlet 34 and 49CFR 173.31 (d)(1)(2), proper securement of a package for disposition and offering for transportation.

column168: On January 17th, 2015 at 01:35 hours, personnel in the CSXT Frontier Yard discovered TILX 191143, a loaded UN 1267, Petroleum Crude Oil tank car to have wetness down the sides of the tank car coming from around the manway. The car was isolated and the Shipper, UET Shipping, LLC, was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2015-01-17-00008. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, EP+S of Vermont the Buffalo branch was dispatched to the scene, upon inspection it was determined that the release was from the manway cover, all swing bolts where tool tight, the cover was opened and the gasket was found to be deteriorated. The nozzle, manway cover and tank car were wiped down, a new nozzle gasket installed the cover was re-secured and tool tightened. Mr. Clarence Vassau, office: 720-563-7937 was notified of the situation found and the corrective action taken. TILX 191143 was released for transport. This incident did NOT require a special move.  Cause Code: 209 (5 points)  NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100

column168: EARLY MONDAY MORNING A LEAKING PACKAGE WAS SPOTTED AT THE WASATCH CLERK AREA. THE PACKAGE HAD NO VISABLE HAZARDOUS MARKINGS BUT WHEN THE RESPONDER BEGAN TO REMOVE THE CONTENTS TO PROCESS THE LEAKED MATERIAL THE BOTTLES HAD A CORROSIVE DIAMOND HAZARD LABEL ON THEM. THE MSDS WAS PRESENT IN THE PACKAGE AND IT LISTED THE CONTENTS AS CORROSIVE IN ITS TRANSPORTATION INFORMATION. AS THE BOX WAS BEING PREPARED FOR DMP PROCESSING AN INVOICE WAS REMOVED FROM A PLASTIC POUCH. ON THE BOX AND WHEN THAT WAS REMOVED A CORROSIVE DIAMOND WARNING LABEL WAS VISIBLE UNDERNEATH THE TRANSPARENT POUCH WITH THIS INFORMATION A CALL WAS MADE TO HMSC AND KATHY ADVICED DAVID TO PROCESS THIS AS AN UNDECLARED HAZMAT (REFERENCE 863659). SIX SIDED PICTURES WERE TAKEN AND A SEVENTH PICTURE SHOWING THE REMOVED INVOICE AND VISIBLE DIAMOND WARNING LABLE WAS ALSO TAKEN. AS THE SHIPPER IS IN THE SAME CITY AS IT WAS DISCOVERED CONTENTS WILL BE HELD FOR PICKUP (AS ADVIZED BY KATHY) BOX WILL BE PROCESSED THROUGH DMP
column169: IT IS RECOMMENDED THAT THE SHIPPER (879545) BE EDUCATED THAT DIAMOND HAZARD LABELS ARE NOT TO BE COVERED WITH INVOICES OR ANYTHING ELSE AND THAT WHEN A DIAMOND HAZARD WARNING LABEL IS PRESENT ON A PACKAGE, BOX, MSDS OR OTHER RELATIVE OBJECT THAT THE SHIPPING INSTRUCTIONS IN THE MSDS BE FOLLOWED.

column168: The shipment was found leaking during the sort. At my direction, FedEx employees opened the box to reveal three inner metal friction lid cans. The cans were inside thin, plastic barrier bags. Can clips were used as positive closure. My experience told me that inner metal friction lid containers greater than 250mL cannot be held in place with can clips, rather a locking ring must be used. Additionally, the shipment contained 11.2 litres of UN 1866, not the 4 litres as stated on the shipping papers. The shipment was held pending an FAA inspection. I advised Hazmat Manager Joe Dallas from the EWR SECFO.

column168: During the unloading phase a 2.5-gallon jerrican was discovered to have released its entire contents by dock personnel. A cleanup contractor was dispatched to the site and advised that all 2.5 gallons was released to the trailer floor and asphalt parking area below due to an apparent fork-lift puncture and/or excessive weight on the package. column168: Intermodal trailer RDWA 18775 was reported leaking liquid from its rear doorway after arrival at the BNSF intermodal facility. RDWA 18775 was isolated at the facility's containment area. Initial inspection noted that the mixed lading within RDWA 18775 had shifted during transit due to insufficient blocking and bracing of the lading. Contract responders reported one 55 gallon poly drum on a wooden pallet near the doorway was leaking.  This drum sustained a bottom puncture from a protruding pallet nail head. The leaking drum was placed and secured in an 85 gallon over-pack drum properly labeled and returned to the lading.  Absorbent material was applied onto observed spilled liquid at the rear interior of RDWA 18775. Afterwards, RDWA 18775 was removed from the BNSF intermodal facility and taken to the nearby YRC terminal were all lading was removed, the spillage on trailer floor was neutralized and pressure washed. The wash rinsate was vacuumed and placed into a disposal tote and other spent cleaning materials placed into two disposal drums, all earmarked for appropriate disposal.

column168: A BNSF train crew reported entrained tank cars BOCX 3013 venting from its side operating cabinet which also had an accumulation of frost/icing.  A BNSF mechanical responder with guidance from the shipper was able to stop the venting. The responder reported closing a vapor valve that was partially open.  It was also reported that no tensioned tie-downs were applied to this handwheeled valve in the operating cabinet which may have allowed this valve to vibrate to an open position.  BOCX 3013 was set-out from its train at a nearby set-out track. On 1/08/2015, BOCX 3013 was re-inspected and no further venting was observed along with no frost or icing on its side operating cabinet. BOCX 3013 was released to proceed to its destination.
column169: No additional comments.

(Hydrochloric Acid) was damaged and released its contents to the cardboard container. A contractor was dispatched and they over packed the good containers to be sent onto the consignee and containerized the damaged one along with all of the cleanup debris and transported the 1-30 gallon drum of waste off site for pending disposal.

During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a customer's site for the purpose of pumping out three tanker-load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transfer operation (on the third tank), the driver needed to clear the hose back into the baker tank at Dow (due to the hose being filled with sludge) Driver opened the valve and started to pressure back into the tank, at that point the rear dome gasket started to squirt out product. A small spill occurred.  Approximately 1 gallon of material had  escaped from the manway.  We shut down operation and the customer addressed the spill with clean sweep, along with cleaning the side of the tanker. Once complete, the driver inspected the manway and gasket and found no issues or deficiencies.
column169: At the time the container was prepared for transportation, driver conduct pre- trip inspection and found everything in compliance. No visible sign of leakage, faulty gaskets or damage to man- ways was observed. It was only after 2 tanks had been emptied and while preparing to empty the third tank did we have an issue.  Drivers will continue to inspect each container, to include dome lids and gaskets, during staging period as well as between pumping activities.  Driver will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity.

column168: On January 20, 2015 at 22:47 hours personnel in the TransFlo Nashville Yard discovered UTLX 200545, a loaded tank car of Hydrogen Peroxide Aqueous Solutions, Stabilized leaking from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Evonik, was notified (CHEMTREC Report #2015-0120-00236).  HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the frangible disc in the non-reclosing pressure relief device had ruptured.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative Kenneth Lewis (251-443-4443).  Contractor personnel installed a new frangible disc and decontaminated the tank car. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. No special move was required.  No QA7.1 filed.     NARRI: 2(5+5+0) x (2+0) = 40  Cause Code: 1004
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 01/21/15 at 1225 hours Florida DOT representative, Vincent Leishman, in the CSXT Edgewood Yard discovered WCHX23159, a loaded tank car of turpentine mixed solution releasing vapors from the manway cover area. The car was isolated and Leaf River Corp (parent Georgia Pacific) was notified via CHEMTREC Report #2015-012100128. HMS manager Harry Hopes and Hazmat Special Agent Trent Page was dispatched to the scene and found bolts 1, 2, 3, and 5 of the manway securement bolts less than tool tight. The  responders also noticed that the waybill required placards of 1299.  The car was displaying placards of 1993. Both issues were identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Tom Davidson (404)652-4052) of Leaf River Corp's parent company Georgia Pacific. The manway securement bolts that were less than tool tight were secured properly and the shipper confirmed that the car had a mixture of turpentine solutions mixed with a flammable liquid, the shipper confirmed that the 1993 placards on the car were correct, and the shipper confirmed that the initial waybill information was incorrect.  The waybill was corrected by the shipper. The car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.    NAR Cause Code: 200 BOLTS/ NUTS-LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT    5(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60 NARRI

column168: At 4:18 hours on January 9, 2015, the loaded tank car, GATX 30160, was reported by KCS Yard staff to be leaking in the Shreveport Yard. All concerned were notified. KCS dispatched hazmat responders to secure the package. Upon arrival the responders determined that approximately 2 gallons of material released on the side of the car with no observable product on the ground. The Manway seal was cut to inspect the manway. 165# Caustic Rated Rupture disk was observed to have ruptured and the manway nozzle gasket was observed in poor condition. The manway gasket was replaced with a new gasket and the rupture disk was replaced with a new 165# Caustic Rated disk. The Manway seal was replaced with new KCS107 seal. The side of the car was decontaminated. The trainmaster was debriefed when hazmat crew was in the clear and car was released back to transportation. column168: At 21:30 hours on January 14, 2015, the Port Arthur Yard reported that the crew on the YPA211-14 noticed a strong "nail polish" odor coming from GATX 95232 parked in the Yard.  No leaks were observed.  KCS dispatched a hazmat responder. Upon arrival the responder determined that  GATX 95232 was not leaking and was secure in all aspects.    To identify the source of the odor, the responder walked the tracks with air monitoring equipment.  In doing so, the responder detected the odor coming from UTLX 640712 - no readings were detected by the equipment.  A full assessment of the tank car showed no closure issues on top of the car; however, the bottom outlet valve (BOV) was found to be iced over due to the commodity being loaded at below freezing temperatures.  No leaks were observed and no measureable meter readings were detected.  The shipper came to the Yard to investigate.  It was assumed that spillage which occurred while loading the car was the source of odor and that the odor would clear once the sun came out and the weather warmed.  Based on this, KCS agreed to return the car for shipping as normal.    The following day, another report of the odor was made in regards to the same tank car (UTLX 640712), but this time the car was observed to be leaking.  The responder returned to the Yard and discovered that the ice that was on the tank car had started to melt giving the appearance of a leak.  The drips were collected in a bucket and were verified to be without odor.  It was determined by KCS and the responder that the BOV needed to be deiced in order to make a better assessment.  Upon completion of the deicing, the entire area surrounding the BOV was dried.  Immediately, a drip coming from the BOV flange bolts was observed.  The drips were collected in a bucket and verified to be Methyl Methacrylate.  All flange bolts were determined to be tight.    Arrangements were made for an imminent field transfer of the tank car to tank trucks.  These transfers occurred on January 17, 2015.  The responder opened the manway lid to verify that the tank car was completely empty.  Upon inspecting the inside of the tank car, the BOV flange gasket was observed not to be centered, possibly causing the leak.  The tank car valves were tagged per FRA OTMA guidelines + "Leaky Tank Car - Do Not Load" was painted on both sides of the car.    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.

column168: On January 27, 2015 at 09:46 hours, FRA Inspector Ryan Tabor at the CSXT Lafayette, Indiana Yard discovered NATX 364173, a loaded UN 1987, Alcohols N.O.S. tank car to have released product from the vapor valve area. The car was isolated and the shipper, Valero Marketing + Supply Company was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2015-01-27-00104. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, Summit, the Indianapolis, IN branch office was dispatched to the scene. Upon inspection it was determined that the 2" vapor valve threads (at base of valve) and 2" pipe nipple threads had been cross threaded and damaged which resulted in the car leaking vapors. Summit removed the 2" vapor valve and pipe nipple, installed the 2" plug and tightened tool tight , CSX crew shook car and Summit inspected for securement and leaks with no further leaks were found. Eagle Railcar was then contracted to replace the vapor valve and to bubble test the car. This was conducted on 1/29/2015.    A HAZMATHOLD was placed on NATX 364173.    Cause Code: 369 at 5 points   NARRI: 5 (5 + 3 + 0) x (2 + 0) = 80

A.  On 01/18/2015 at 15:35 EST, a private citizen notified Chemtrec of a odor being released from three rail cars on a siding track in Bay Minette Alabama. The CPDX 582049 is a loaded Molten Sulfur tank car releasing vapor from the rupture disk assembly area. The shipper, Chevron Products and Chemtrec were notified. (CHEMTREC Report #2015011800034). Chris Machenberg, a CSXT hazardous materials manager, was dispatched to the scene and found improper bolts for the rupture disk assembly.All three bolts were in place. Two of the three bolts were not the correct style of bolts and the third bolt was siezed by corrosion The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Billy Burrell 228-938-4260 .The PRV assembly was secured at the time of the incident. Frit Rail car performed the first repair on 01/20/2015. Frit Car replaced the entire manway lid,gasket and rupture disk assembly. On sunday 1/25/2015 a odor was emmitted from the CPDX 582049 again and CSX Hazardous Materials manager Chris Machenberg was dispatched and found that the PRV studs had the wrong nuts applied and the threads appeared damaged. A temporary repair was made. on 1/26/2015 Frit Car, Chevron, USES (a CSX hazmat response contractor), and Chris Machenberg, CSX Hazmat Manager, were dispatched  to make the final repair. I was discovered at this time that Frit Car had used a Durlon 900 gasket in the previous repair. This was not the prper gasket, Chevron uses a Garlock 3000 gasket. It was also discovered that the nuts used on the PRV where not the correct size. A new manway lid was installed and the proper gasket was used and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 required is not required.       CPDX 582049:  Cause Code:427 and for Frit Car repair - 210  NARRI: 5(5+1+0) x (2+0)= 60    B.On 01/18/2015 at 15:35 EST, a private citizen notified Chemtrec of a odor being released from three rail cars on a siding track in Bay Minette Alabama. The CPDX 582123 is a loaded Molten Sulfur tank car releasing vapor from the rupture disk assembly area. The shipper, Chevron Products and Chemtrec were notified. (CHEMTREC Report #2015011800034). Chris Machenberg, a CSXT hazardous materials manager, was dispatched to the scene and found the rupture disk was heavily corroded. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Billy Burrell 228-938-4260 .The rupture disk was replaced with a new rupture disk. No special switching moves were needed and a QA 7.1 will not be required. column168: Entrained tank car UTLX 213174 was reported with commodity on its side shell after arrival in the railyard. UTLX 213174 was set-out from its train (U-TIOFTE0-01T) and isolated at the facility's containment area. No ground impact from spillage was reported. Contract responders inspecting UTLX 213174 reported finding its liquid line valve closed, but not in the locked position, with its closure plug not tool tight. Responders placed the liquid valve in the locked position and tool tightened its closure plug 3 full turns which ended any further commodity release at the liquid valve's valve port closure. Responder's hot water pressure washed the ice covered spillage from UTLX 213174. All rinsate was captured in the containment pit for processing at the facility's oil-water separator.

column168: The truck ran off Interstate 24 near mile marker 162 near Jasper,TN. The tractor/trailer, cargo tank went off the roadway to the left landing in a creek bed between the east and west bound lanes of I-24. In the roll over, the front clean out nozzle was pushed back causing a breach in the tank.  This was “Extreme dynamic loads in excess of those suggested in 49 CFR 178.345-3 resulted in a moment about the subject nozzle, causing the pipe to tear from the thin-walled pressure vessel.” This resulted in the release of approximately 3,500 gallons of resin solution into the creek over a period of several hours.     Local emergency responders were not able to stop the leak but were able to place absorbent boom downstream to contain the material. The material was loaded at 150°F. As the material released into the cold creek water, it immediately cooled and began to cling together staying in an area within 100 yards of the cargo tank. Environmental remediation crews were brought in the day of the event and for a total of  6 days, those crews worked to contain and remove the released material from the creek. Absorbent boom and catch fences were left in place until the first rain after the product release. Several days after the rain they were checked. There was no material found in the booms or catch fences so they were removed from the creek.

column25: Tesoro Refining + Marketing Company by Hess Corp./Watco
column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: BNSF was notified of possible leaking entrained tank cars in a BNSF unit train (U-TIOFTE0-01T). This train was inspected upon arrival at the BNSF's Vancouver railyard. Inspection results identified seven entrained tank cars with commodity on their top side shells and these seven tank cars were set-out of the train for further inspection and cleaning.  These seven tank cars were all DOT 111S100W1's, built in 2012 and the spillage on their side shells estimated at 2 gallons or less per tank car. All seven tank cars were identified as leaking at their liquid valves (3 inch McKenzie ball valves) that had loose closure plugs with the liquid valves in the closed position but the ball valves in the closed position were not completely sealing.  Responders relieved internal pressure within these tank cars and reseated the liquid valves.  The less than tool tight closure plugs were removed, Teflon tape sealant applied to their threaded areas, exposed valve ports cleaned, the plugs reapplied and properly tool tightened. Residual spillage on the tank car shells were cleaned. All securement and cleaning was accomplished by 0145 hrs. PST,  1/13/2015. These seven tank cars were re-inspected in the afternoon of 1/13/2015 with no observed leakage. The equipment ID's for these seven tank cars follow;  UTLX 213180  UTLX 213016  UTLX 213006  UTLX 212781  UTLX 212779  UTLX 212797  UTLX 212816    OTMA FRA-150116R8V (1 of 3) was granted to transport these seven tank cars to the consignee for unloading.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column25: Tesoro Refining + Marketing Company by Hess Corp./Watco
column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: After previous events of leaking entrained tank cars in a BNSF unit train (U-TIOFTE0-01T). This train was re-inspected upon arrival at the BNSF's Auburn railyard. Inspection results identified an additional six entrained tank cars with commodity on their top side shells and these tank cars were set-out of the train for further inspection and cleaning.  These six tank cars were all DOT 111S100W1's, built in 2012 and the spill on their side shells estimated at 1 gallon or less per tank car with the exception of UTLX 212850 estimated at approximately 5 gallons. All six tank cars were identified as leaking at their liquid valves that had loose closure plugs with the liquid valves in the closed position. The liquid valves (3 inch McKenzie ball valves) were not seating/sealing properly in the closed position. Responders relieved internal pressure within these tank cars and reseated the liquid valves. The less than tool tight closure plugs were removed, Teflon tape sealant applied to their threaded areas, the exposed valve ports were cleaned, the closure plugs reapplied and properly tool tightened. Residual spillage on the tank car shells were cleaned. All securement and cleaning was accomplished on 1/14/2015. No further leakage from the liquid valves were observed afterwards.  The equipment ID's for these six tank cars follow;  UTLX 212850  UTLX 213021  UTLX 212756  UTLX 212831  UTLX 212830  UTLX 212979    OTMA FRA-150116R8V (2 of 3) was granted to transport these six tank cars to the consignee for unloading.

column25: Tesoro Refining + Marketing Company by Hess Corp./Watco
column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: After previous events of leaking entrained tank cars in a BNSF unit train (U-TIOFTE0-01T). This train was re-inspected upon arrival at the BNSF's Auburn railyard. Inspection results identified an additional six entrained tank cars with commodity on their top side shells and these tank cars were set-out of the train for further inspection and cleaning.  These six tank cars were all DOT 111S100W1's, built in 2012 and the spill on their side shells estimated at 1 gallon or less per tank car with the exception of UTLX 212850 estimated at approximately 5 gallons. All six tank cars were identified as leaking at their liquid valves that had loose closure plugs with the liquid valves in the closed position. The liquid valves (3 inch McKenzie ball valves) were not seating/sealing properly in the closed position. Responders relieved internal pressure within these tank cars and reseated the liquid valves. The less than tool tight closure plugs were removed, Teflon tape sealant applied to their threaded areas, the exposed valve ports were cleaned, the closure plugs reapplied and properly tool tightened. Residual spillage on the tank car shells were cleaned. All securement and cleaning was accomplished on 1/14/2015. No further leakage from the liquid valves were observed afterwards.  The equipment ID's for these six tank cars follow;  UTLX 212850  UTLX 213021  UTLX 212756  UTLX 212831  UTLX 212830  UTLX 212979    OTMA FRA-150116R8V (2 of 3) was granted to transport these six tank cars to the consignee for unloading.

column168: THE GIANT RESOURCE RECOVERY-SUMTER, INC. (GRR) RAIL HEAD FACILITY IS A 10-DAY TRANSFER FACILITY. ON JANUARY 6, 2015, A LEAK WAS OBSERVED COMING FROM A ROLL-OFF BOX THAT CONTAINED SOLID HAZARDOUS WASTE MATERIAL. PLASTIC WAS PLACED BENEATH THE PERIMETER OF THE BACK DOOR OF THE ROLL-OFF BOX. A CATCH PAN WAS PLACED ON TOP OF THE PLASTIC ALONG WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO COLLECT THE LEAKING MATERIAL. THE LEAK WAS STOPPED/CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 30 MINUTES AFTER THE LEAK WAS OBSERVED. AS A CONSERVATIVE MEASURE, SOIL THAT WAS POTENTIALLY IMPACTED BENEATH THE ROLL-OFF BOX WAS EXCAVATED THE SAME DAY AND PLACED IN A DRUM FOR DISPOSAL. THE BACK DOOR OF THE ROLL-OFF BOX WAS TIGHTENED AND THE LEAKED STOPPED COMPLETELY. NO ADDITIONAL LEAKS WERE OBSERVED. THE REMAINING MATERIALS THAT WERE USED TO CONTAIN THE SPILL WERE PLACED IN THE SAME DRUM.
column169: MAINTENANCE AND THE USE OF AN ADDITIONAL LINED WITHIN THE ROLL-OFF BOX MAY IMPROVE THE CAPABILITY OF THE CONTAINER TO HOLD ANY LIQUID MATERIALS. GRR WILL CONTINUE TO CONDUCT DAILY INSPECTIONS OF THE CONTAINERS.  IN ADDITION, GRR WILL ALSO TIGHTEN THE DOORS ON THE BOXES ONCE THEY ARE OFF-LOADED FROM THE RAIL CAR AND STAGED FOR INTERMITTENT STORAGE.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 10:30 AM, AN OPERATOR BEGAN LOADING TRAILER T-7L WITH 3000 GALLONS OF ACS GRADE 96% SULFURIC ACID. THIS IS A 3500 GALLON TRAILER, AT 11:30, MULTIPLE PVS EMPLOYEES IN THE AREA NOTICED LIQUID ON THE GROUND IN THE LOADING AREA AND NOTIFIED THE OPERATOR WHO IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE LOAD PUMP. ACID INITIALLY OVERFLOWED THROUGH THE 1 INCH VENT LINE ON THE TRAILER THEN SUFFICIENT PRESSURE BUILT UP TO OPEN THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE. BASED ON CHANGES IN STORAGE TANK LEVELS, NEARLY 250 GALLONS OF ACID SPILLED. SOME OF THE ACID WAS CONTAINED IN THE CURBED CONTAINMENT AREA AROUND THE LOADING SPOT AND WAS PUMPED INTO A TOTE.  HOWEVER, THE MAJORITY OF THE ACID SPILLED OVER INTO THE PAVEMENT TO THE EAST. NO ONE WAS INJURED AND NONE OF THE ACID REACHED THE OUTFALLS TO THE BUFFALO RIVER. A CREW SPREAD SODA ASK TO NEUTRALIZE THEIR ACID AND SPEEDI-DRY TO CONTAIN IT. THE MATERIAL WAS SWEPT UP AND PUT INTO CUBIC YARD BOXES FOR DISPOSAL. THE TRAILER WAS THOROUGHLY RINSED WITH WATER AND THE EXCESS 500 GALLONS WAS BLOWN OFF INTO A STORAGE TANK BEFORE SHIPMENT.
column169: PVS will review procedures to ensure they were followed and verify-computerized loading systems were working properly.

column168: THE RELEASED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS IN A METAL CAGED PLASTIC TOTE AND LOADED ON TO A FLATBED STRAIGHT TRUCK. THE TOTE WAS SECURED TO THE FRONT OF THE LOAD BEARING SURFACE WITH TWO 2" SYNTHETIC TIE DOWNS. THERE WAS SNOW ON THE GROUND FROM WINTER WEATHER RECEIVED THE NIGHT BEFORE AND THE METAL BED OF THE TRUCK WAS COVERED IN SNOW PRIOR TO LOADING THE TOTES. THE TRUCK DEPARTED THE FACILITY APPROXIMATELY 2 HOURS AFTER BEING LOADED. WITHIN APPROXIMATELY 1 MILE OF THE FACILITY, THE DRIVER MADE A LEFT TURN AT AN INTERSECTION. DURING THE TURN AND JUST OUTSIDE THE INTERSECTION, THE TIE DOWN FAILED AND ONE TOTE SLID OFF THE PASSENGER SIDE OF THE TRUCK LANDING UPON THE ASPHALT ROADWAY. UPON STRIKING THE ROAD, THE PLASTIC TOTE SLIGHTLY RUPTURED ALONG THE SIDE SPILLING APPROXIMELY 44 GALLONS OF THE PRODUCT ON THE ROADWAY. THE DRIVER AND ANOTHER FELLOW EMPLOYEE QUICKLY POSITIONED THE TOTE WITHIN MINUTES MITIGATING THE RELEASE OF THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE TOTE.  OTHER EMPLOYEES WERE SUMMONED TO THE SCENE ALONG WITH EMERGENCY RESPONDERS.  EMERGENCY RESPONDERS DETOURED TRAFFIC AROUND THE SCENE, WHILE COMPANY EMPLOYEES APPLIED ABSORBENT MATERIALS TO THE ROADWAY MINIMIZING THE SPREAD OF THE PRODUCT.  THE REMAINING MATERIAL WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER CAGED TOTE AND LATER TAKEN AWAY FROM THE SCENE BY EMPLOYEES. AN ENVIRONMENT SERVICE COMPANY WAS CALED TO THE SCENE TO FINALIZE THE CLEANUP AND DISPOSE OF ANY WASTE.
column169: Upon reviewing the circumstances of this incident, it was determined the totes should have been loaded on the bed of the truck free from snow and ice, and/or, blocked and braced from any lateral or rearward movement. The totes were braced from any forward movement.

column168: On 01/28/2015, at 10:59, personnel in the CSXT Rice Yard discovered DOWX 73171, a loaded tank car of Methyl acrylate, stabilized, leaking from the bottom outlet valve. The car was isolated and the shipper DOW Chemical Company, the Waycross fire department, the Georgia Department of Natural Recourses, and the NRC were notified as well as CHEMTREC, report # 2015-01-28-00106.  SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a release coming from the area of the packing gland nut on the bottom outlet valve.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, DOW Chemical Company Christopher Harvey, phone number 979-238-3130.  Contractor personnel tightened the packing gland nut and placed absorbent material around the nut and returned on 02/05/2015 to transfer the contents of the tank car.  Once the transfer was complete the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. A is 7.1 required.    Cause Code:  NARRI:

column168: Tank car BNSF 880632 was reported dripping commodity from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) in the railyard. BNSF mechanical responders placed absorbent padding and a catch basin under BNSF 880632's BOV to catch the commodity drips. The bottom operated BOV was inspected. The BOV was closed, its closure plug was secure along with its mounting flange bolt nuts. A compromised BOV mounting flange gasket was suspected as being the cause of the commodity release.  BNSF 880632 was fully unloaded by 1600 hrs. MST 1/16/2015 which ended any further commodity drips from the BOV. The amount of diesel fuel unloaded was compared to the gallons billed from the originating loading facility to determine a variance or an estimate of possible commodity loss.  A remediation contractor excavated impacted ballast and soils at the observed ground spillage areas followed by a treatment of Micro-Blaze to those areas. Collected impacted materials were earmarked for appropriate disposal.  BNSF 880632 was directed to the nearest qualified repair facility for BOV repairs and failure analysis.

column168: Tank car UTLX 200193 was reported with commodity staining on its side shell while in the railyard. No ground impact from any spillage was observed. Contract responder's initial inspection of UTLX 200193 indicated no active leaking observed and responders proceeded to clean the residual and non-evaporated spillage from UTLX 200193's side shell.  Later on 1/19/2015, the contract responders re-inspected UTLX 200193 and found commodity seeping from UTLX 200193's liquid valve's closure plug's threaded connection. The liquid valve was reported in the closed position and likely not fully sealing in the closed position. The liquid valve's closure plug was loosened and Teflon tape sealant applied to its exposed threaded area.  The closure plug was tool tightened. Afterwards, no further commodity leak was observed from liquid valve's closure plug's threaded connection.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On 1/20/2015, BNSF was notified by the Rarus Railway Co. (RARW) that tank car ACFX 79474 standing on the interchange track in the BNSF railyard since 1/13/2015 was being refused in interchange due to its bottom outlet valve (BOV) dripping commodity. After this notification, the local BNSF trainmaster visually inspected ACFX 79474 on two occasions and did not observe any dripping from ACFX 79474's BOV. Contract responders were called to inspect ACFX 79474. On 1/21/2015, responders reported that ACFX 79474's BOV was in the closed position, but its closure plug was not tool tight which allowed commodity to drip from the closure plug's threaded connection.  The responder's tool tightened the BOV closure plug by 1000 hrs. MST, 1/21/2015. It appeared that the BOV in the closed position was not fully sealing. Afterwards, the BOV was monitored and no further commodity drips were observed. Responder's cleaned all commodity from the BOV surfaces and shoveled droplet impacted ice/snow directly under the BOV into a poly drum for appropriate future disposal.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column58: O-Ring or Seals; Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: While inspecting car, vapor was detected leaking from the pressure relief valve.  Car was gauged and determined not to be overloaded.  Closer inspection revealed the O-rings within the O-ring retaining cap had failed.  Shipper was contacted, and arrangements were made with Rescar Mobil Rail Repair to replace failed O-rings with new Viton O-rings.  A pressure test was conducted on the car with no further leakage detected; home shop stickers were applied to left and right sides of car and the car was released to continue in transportation.
column169: Conduct proper pre and post inspection of car upon completion of loading or unloading, to ensure all valves, fittings and closures are in a closed and secure condition preventing release of liquid, vapor or gas while car is in transportation.

column62: Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Over-pressurized
column168: On January 27, 2015 at 0217 Hours train Q19827 derailed after entering a siding in Martin, South Carolina. As a result of the train entering the siding the lead locomotive struck tank cars stored on the track. The locomotive CSXT3097 struck UTLX664048 (non hazardous residue dye) and UTLX130390 (Hydrochloric Acid).    UTLX130390, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric acid sustained severe damage due to the impact. The car was breached on the A and  B end of the container, releasing its contents. Photographs of the damaged tank car are attached to the report.    The Shipper, OLIN Corporation was notified via CHEMTREC report number 2015-0127-00028.    Martin and Allendale County Fire Departments were dispatched to the site and evacuated one nearby residential home and as a precautionary measure closed State Highway 125 and Chert Quarry Road.    ATARI Cause Code: 662 Train derailment    2(5+5+0) X (5+4) = 180 ATARI    On January 27, 2015 at 0217 Hours train Q19827 derailed after entering a siding in Martin, S.C. As a result of the derailment 2 Locomotive, 8 Intermodal cars, striking tank cars that had previously been placed on the siding track.  TILX160786 was shoved approximately 125 yards down the siding track and did not derail.    TILX160786, a loaded tank car of Sodium Hydroxide sustained A end damage which activated the pressure relief device valve, releasing approximately one gallon of product onto side of the container. Photographs of the damaged tank car are attached to the report.    The Shipper, OLIN Corporation was notified via CHEMTREC report number 2015-0127-00028.    Martin and Allendale County Fire Departments were dispatched to the site and evacuated one nearby residential home and a precautionary measure closed State Highway 125 and Chert Quarry Road. column168: On January 27, 2015 at 0217 Hours train Q19827 derailed after entering a siding in Martin, South Carolina. As a result of the train entering the siding the lead locomotive struck tank cars stored on the track. The locomotive CSXT3097 struck UTLX664048 (non hazardous residue dye) and UTLX130390 (Hydrochloric Acid).    UTLX130390, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric acid sustained severe damage due to the impact. The car was breached on the A and  B end of the container, releasing its contents. Photographs of the damaged tank car are attached to the report.    The Shipper, OLIN Corporation was notified via CHEMTREC report number 2015-0127-00028. column168: It was reported that the tote's lid was left off during transit, causing approximately 2 cups of material to splash out of the opening throughout transit. Groendyke driver unloading a load of unleaded gasoline when a customer at the convenience store was not paying attention and ran over our drop fitting. Upon impact the fitting broke and product began to spew from the hose. The driver shut down the unloading process as fast as he could, set out spill pads and had help from the consignee to clean up the product once contained.
column169: The driver had all cones out and tried to get customers attention before hitting the drop fitting. Groendyke cannot predict irresponsible actions by others.

column168: On January 28, 2015, a 330-gallon plastic tote of UN2693 Bisulfites, Aqueous Solutions, NOS was damaged during loading operations. Approximately 1/2 gallon of material was found to be released from the tote upon arrival at the R&L Terminal in Arlington, TN. Terminal personnel conducted the minimal clean-up and requested a transfer of the remaining material. United States Environmental Services (USES) responded to transfer the remaining material as the integrity of the tote was compromised. The old tote was taken for disposal.

column168: A company owned/operated tractor/dry bulk combination was transporting 43,000 pounds of bulk, division 1.5D (UN 0331), ammonium nitrate fuel oil, under special permit 4453, when an accident occurred at 8:19 AM, on Springdale Rd., just one mile from the final destination.  As a result of the accident, the driver was injured, the roadway closed, and a spill of 3,000 pounds of the cargo.   The weather conditions were cold and rainy, and there was ice present on the road, which is a 2 lane asphalt county road in Northern Kentucky. The speed limit on the road is 55, except in curves where suggested speeds range between 25 and 35.  The driver was traveling at an average speed of around 24 MPH in the minutes prior to the accident. The driver had made this trip on previous occasions, but on this trip he was concerned with the road’s surface conditions as he descended a 3% grade, and made a precautionary decision to reduce his speed.  At the time of the accident, The Vehicle’s PeopleNet system indicated his speed at 24 mph.   In the accident area, the roadway entered an area shaded from the sun, the roadway’s superelevation titled to the downhill lane, and there was a curve with a drainage ditch. These conditions and the driver’s attempt to slow The Vehicle further by “tapping the brakes”, led to the vehicle sliding off the roadway into the ditch on its passenger side. The spill was caused when some of the manholes on the top of the dry bulk trailer were torn off.  First responders extricated the driver from the truck, and transported him to the hospital with non-life threatening injuries.  the spill was cleaned up by a qualified third party, hired by the company's spill emergency response firm.  The cargo was transloaded into another vehicle.
column169: The driver, who had over 10 years of experience in driving combination vehicles, and was Smith System trained, was re-trained in the 5 keys of the Smith System, with emphasis on vehicular control and weather conditions.  He will also have adequate time to recover from the accident prior to his return to driving.  The company shared the accident information throughout the organization in the form of a "safety alert"

column168: THE KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER DIESEL FUEL INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.

column168: ON MONDAY, JANUARY 12, 2015, POOLSURE, LOCATED AT 567 3RD STREET HOLLY HILL, FLORIDA 32117, WAS SCHEDULED TO RECEIVE A BULK DELIVERY OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE (UN1791, HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS, 8, PGIII). THE SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE WAS BEING TRANSPORTED BY TRANSPORTATION SERVICES UNLIMITED INC. ("TSUI") IN A DOT-SPECIAL PERMIT CARGO TANKER (DOT-SP 10878). THE CARGO TANKER (UNIT 1626) AND TRACTOR (UNIT 2626) WERE OPERTATED BY TSUI A COMMERCIAL MOTOR VEHICLE OPERATOR. THE OPERATOR HOLDS A CURRENT COMMERCIAL MOTOR VEHICLE DRIVER'S LICENSE FROM THE STATE OF FLORIDA WITH HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND CARGO TANKER ENDORSEMENTS. HE HAS BEEN EMPLOYED WITH TSUI SINCE JANUARY 27, 2014, HAVING SUCCESSFULLY PASSED ALL BACKGROUND INVESTIGATION REQUIREMENTS AS WELL AS TRAINING REQUIRED UNDER 49 CFR 172 SUBPART H. THIS WAS THE DRIVER'S FIRST DELIVERY TO THE POOLSURE FACILITY. THE TSUI OPERATOR CURRENTLY REMAINS HOSPITALIZED AND IS INCAPABLE OF PROVIDING INFORMATION.  ACCORDINGLY, THE CIRCUMSTANCES SURROUNDING THE DELIVERY, AND TIMES SET FORTH HEREIN WERE COMPILED FROM POOLSURE'S SURVEILLANCE VIDEOTAPE, TELEPHONE RECORDS AND THE DELIVERY VEHICLE'S ELECTRONIC ON-BOARD RECORDING SYSTEM. ALL TIMES ARE EASTERN STANDARD TIME.    THE OPERTATOR ARRIVED AT THE POOLSURE FACILITY IN HOLLY HILL AT 16:39.  IT WAS DAYLIGHT, BUT WEATHER CONDITIONS WERE POOR, THERE WAS HEAVY RAIN. POOLSURE HAD CLOSED. THERE WERE NO POOLSURE PERSONNEL AT THE PREMISES, BUT THE TSUI OPERATOR HAD BEEN PROVIDED A GATE CODE TO ENTER THE FACILITY. HOWEVER, THE CODE FAILED WHEN HE ATTEMPTED TO USE IT. FOR APPROXIMATELY THE NEXT HOUR, THE TSUI OPERATOR WAITED WHILE ATTEMPTS BY HIM AND THE TSUI DISPATCHER WERE MADE TO CONTACT POOLSURE PERSONNEL. THE CORRECT CODE TO ENTER THE FACILITY WAS OBTAINED FROM POOLSURE A REPRESENTATIVE AND PROVIDED TO THE TSUI OPERATOR VIA THE TELEPHONE. TSUI OPERATOR USED THE NEW CODE, OPENED THE GATE AND BACKED THE TRACTOR-CARGO TANKER INTO THE FACILITY TO THE CUSTOMER ABOVEGROUND STROAGE TANKS. HOWEVER, THESE TANKS WERE NOT SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE TANKS, THE TANKS WERE LABELED ACID AND HAD A US DOT CORROSIVE LABEL DISPLAYING THE UNITED NATION IDENTIFICATION NUMBER 2796. FROM THE TIME THE TSUI OPERATOR BACKED HIS TRACTOR-CARGO TANKER INTO THE FACILITY TO APPROXIMATELY 17:51, TSUI OPERATOR CONDUCTED VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE RECEIVING CUSTOMER TANKS, WALKED AROUND THE TANKS, CONNECTED HIS CARGO TANKER TO THE CUSTOMER TANK CONNECTION PORT FOR LOADING AND BEGAN UNLOADING SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE INTO THE CUSTOMER TANK MARKED ACID.  AT APPROXIMATELY 17:51, TSUI OPERATOR APPARENTLY WAS AWARE OF PROBLEM, AND WALKED TOWARD THE STREET. HE RETURNED TWICE TO THE CONNECTION POINT AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER, WITH AND WITHOUT AN ESCAPE RESPIRATOR. AFTER THE SECOND ATTEMTP TO RETURN, HE WALKED TOWARDS 3RD STREET.    HOLLY HILL FIRE DEPARTMENT ALARM NOTIFICATION OCCURRED AT 18:01. THE INITIAL REPORT WAS A CHLORINE RELEASE. UPON ARRIVING AT THE SCENE AT 18:08, HOLLY HILL ENGINE 96 CREW SPOKE TO THE TSUI OPERATOR. ACC

column168: The driver was traveling north on Route 92 on 1/23/2015.  As documented in the police report, ice and snow covered roads caused the tanker to slide off the roadway and become disconnected from the truck.  The tanker rolled and was positioned within an unnamed tributary of Anthony Creek of the Greenbrier River.  Greenbrier County Homeland Security and Emergency Services, two local fire departments, an environmental contractor responded to the incident to assist with containing the approximately 3,975 gallons of diesel that had spilled.    The diesel fuel spilled from the drop tubes, which were damaged in the accident.  The duration of the release was approximately six hours.  The release was stopped when Woodford Transport was able to pump the remaining diesel fuel into another tanker and the tanker was removed from the unnamed tributary.  The leak was reported to the West Virginia Department of Environmental Protection (WVDEP) and the National Response Center.       Steps were immediately taken to contain the diesel at the accident site; however an unknown quantity entered Anthony Creek.  Woodford retained the services of two additional spill response contractors to assist.  The WVDEP requested assistance from the United States Environmental Protection Agency (USEPA).  The USEPA and US Coast Guard assisted with placement of river and absorbent boom within Anthony Creek and the Greenbrier River.  As a precautionary measure, two public water intakes located on the Greenbrier River were closed and eventually reopened following water testing indicated no diesel was present.  Remediation at the accident site is nearly complete as of 2/19/2015.  As a precautionary measure, boom is being maintained within the unnamed tributary, Anthony Creek, and Greenbrier River. Refer to the attached site map and photos.
column169: Woodford Transport's driver was not found to be at fault for the accident.  However, Woodford Transport will perform additional training regarding driving when ice and snow conditions may be present.

column168: On 01/26/2015 at 14:15, the Kansas City Southern Mossville Yard in Westlake, LA reported a foul odor.  The Environmental + Hazmat Department mobilized a response contractor to the yard to assess and conduct air monitoring.    The source of the odor was identified from tank car GATX 44890.  The odor was determined to be coming from the top fitting protective housing.      Upon opening the protective housing, the responder clearly saw free liquid around the base of the vacuum relief valve.  The air valve plug was removed and the valve opened to verify 0 pressure on the tank car.  Upon removal of the protective cap on the relief valve, the internal spring mechanism was seen to be misaligned and not seating correctly.  This misalignment was due to trash present on the sealing surface.    The shipper came to the yard and a new vacuum relief valve was installed.  The car was returned to home-shop under a FRA OTMA where leak / pressure testing occurred and the tank car recertified.    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: Intermodal trailer CXTI 31 was reported leaking a black paint like substance after its arrival at the BNSF intermodal facility. CXTI 31 was carefully moved to the facility's containment area. Contract responder's inspection of CXTI 31 revealed one stainless steel IBC (UN Specification 31A/Y/05-01/USA/M4070) with a hazardous material label indicating a flammable 1263 material was coated with expelled  paint commodity (a black gloss truck bed coating) along with the trailer's interior left sidewall. The IBC's top opening/fill port's closure lid had popped open expelling liquid paint material. The responders closed and secured the fill port lid and cleaned the paint material from the outside of the IBC. The splashed paint inside CXTI 31 was cleaned. Afterwards, lading was returned inside the cleaned CXTI 31. Appropriate placards were applied onto the exterior of CXTI 31.   The bill of lading from the paint manufacturer indicated that 8 IBC's of hazardous material (UN 1263, Paint, Class 3, PG II) were in this shipment and this information was not passed to the BNSF at the time of initial rail transit by the shipper carrier (CAL-x Trans).
column169: Ensure shipper carrier provides accurate hazardous material shipping information and documentation for hazardous material intermodal shipments. The carrier CAL-x Trans Inc. was counseled by a BNSF LARS (Load and Ride Solutions) representative on required identification and appropriate hazardous material descriptions on bills of lading presented for rail transportation.

column168: 1/23/15: At approximately 11:30AM, while switching Metuchen Yard, CR Conductor of CR ME05 noted bottom outlet of tank car RAIX 6553, load, Corrosive Liquid, Acidic, Organic, NOS (Isopentanoic Acid) to have product dripping.    TM D. Robertson contacted CR Risk Manager A. Richter, who dispatched Hepaco, CR environmental/emergency response contractor to the yard to inspect and remediate.  Further inspection noted the bottom outlet dripping from up inside the skid protection where the valve is mounted to the tank shell.  Additionally dripping noted originating from the bottom outlet valve operating stem as well.  Attempts to secure both areas were minimally successful.  Valve wrapped in chemical absorbant pads and poly wrap with duct tape.  This is the serving yard for the customer, so the car was moved with authorization of the customer, to their unloading rack for further handling.  Car to be unloaded and OTMA to be obtained by Dow Chemical for car to be moved to shop for inspection/repair/replacement of bottom outlet valve.

ERTS was contacted by Troy Shelley of Ruan Transportation regarding a tanker release of UN1824 Sodium Hydroxide Solution. It was reported that on 1/28, driver overfilled the tank at customer location, releasing an estimated 10 gallons of product due to not following proper procedures. The release impacted the tank, concrete wall, rafters and pad. It was reported that no soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release.The release was immediate and impacted an area on the tank approximately 20 ft high x 8 ft across and an area of floor approximately 15 ft x 30 ft and a 20ft x 20 ft of roof of an adjacent structure.  A network contractor was dispatched and completed the clean up of the tank and inside of the building.

column168: Traveling north on Locke Valley Road; there are two 180 degree turns going down the north side; truck entered the first turn which was snow covered; driver reduced speed; entering second turn, snow was covering glare ice in the center and across the right side of the road; the rear tires lost traction and began to slide; the driver countered the slide and the truck skidded the opposite direction; corrected again and by this time the truck was on the opposite shoulder and nearly stopped, the driver said the truck rocked toward the road and then rocked back toward the shoulder and went over onto its left side. The impact of the truck going over cracked a fitting on the rear of the truck, causing a minor leak. Heller's mitigation team stopped the leak with a wet cloth wrapping and clamp.
column169: Townships need to take better care of areas where run-off creates areas where water runs across roadways creating glare and black ice conditions. These areas should be well known to the township and steps should have been taken to correct the problem. The icy roadway was made even more hazardous by the snow cover, the road had not been plowed or cindered at the time of the accident.

DRIVER WAS DELIVERING LOAD OF STYRENE TO GOODYEAR TIRE AND RUBBER IN HOUSTON, TX.  GOODYEAR OPERATOR CAME OUT AND TOLD TRIMAC DRIVER TO GROUND HIS UNIT AND THE WHEELS.  OPERATOR DIRECTED TRIMAC DRIVER TO CUT THE LOAD CABLE OFF OF THE DISCHARGE CAP.  THE GOODYEAR OPERATOR SAID HE WOULD SET UP THE SYSTEM TO OFF LOAD THE PRODUCT.  TRIMAC DRIVER WENT TO THE HOSE RACK AND SAW THAT THE END PLUG OF THE CUSTOMER OFF LOADING HOSE WAS CHAINED TO THE HOSE RACK.  TRIMAC ASKED IF HE WOULD REMOVE THE CHAIN AND TAKE THE PLUG OUT WITH THE CUSTOMER OWNED HOSE ON THE GROUND.  HE WAS INSTRUCTED TO TAKE THE HOSE OUT WITH IT CHAINED TO THE RACK.  TRIMAC DRIVER BENT OVER HOSE (ABOUT 2.5 FEET OFF THE GROUND)  AND REMOVED THE END PLUG.  THERE WAS A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT STILL IN HOSE UNDER PRESSURE.  THE CUSTOMER OWNED CHECK VALVE HAD LEAKED BACK INTO THE HOSE.  THE OPERATOR DID NOT RELIEVE ALL THE PRESSURE IN THE CUSTOMER HOSE.  THE STYRENE UNDER PRESSURE SPRAYED FROM THE HOSE.  THE TRIMAC DRIVER HAD PRODUCT SPRAYED ON HIS FACE, INTO HIS EYES, AND ON HIS CHEST AND WAIST AREA.
column169: MET WITH CUSTOMER HIS DISCUSS THE INCIDENT.  THE CUSTOMER REPLACED TEH VALVES ON THE SYSTEM AND PUMP.  BEFORE ALL DELIVERS TO THE TRIMAC SUPERVISION DISCUSSES THE OPERATION AT THE CUSTOMER AT ASSURE COMPLIANCE WITH ALL OFF LOADING PROCEDURES.  ALSO TO ASSURE ALL PRESSURE IS RELIEVED ON OFF LOADING HOSE AND THERE IS NO PRODUCT IN THE HOSE.

column168: WHILE ATTEMPTING TO DISCHARGE PRODUCT FROM THE CARGO TANK TO THE FACILITY STORAGE TANK THE DISCHARGE HOSE RUPTURED. column168: The following serves as Sun Coast Resources (SCRI) report on the spill at Highway 181 in Falls City, Texas, in Karnes County.    Initial Notification:  Susan Tyler, the Environmental Compliance Manager with Sun Coast Resources, reported the spill on January 11, 2015, to 1-800-832-8224. Incident# 20150153 was assigned the spill.    Status of Spill:  Spill response actions are complete. Detailed description is listed below.     Response Chronology:  On January 10, 2015, Sun Coast Resources driver Robert Carmickle rolled over SCRI Unit No. 70034/1608 as a result of vehicular accident. During transfer of the crude oil from the trailer it was noted that ventilation system was damaged during the accident and approximately 420 gallons of crude spilled into an adjacent waterway off Highway 181 just outside of Falls City, Texas. The spill was discovered at 1:30 AM on 1/11/2015 and was immediately reported to our internal spill response team.     The SCRI spill response team consisting of Jake Pena, Mark Doise, Susan Tyler and Stratton Williams and spill contractor Clean Tank Inc. (CTI), arrived on site on 1/11/2015.    Meteorology:  Weather conditions during the spill response were cold and rainy and did increase the spread of the spill in the waterway until containment booms were utilized.     Reported Injuries:  There were no injuries or fatalities associated with this spill.    Remediation of Contamination:  The spilled crude oil was removed from the water body by utilizing a skimmer and booms. Approximately 400 gallons of oily water was removed and           transported via a vacuum truck to be temporarily stored at the SCRI San Antonio facility prior to shipment to the SCRI Houston facility for aggregation and disposal at a licensed vendor.    Sampling and Analysis:  No soil sampling or laboratory analysis was conducted since the spill occurred over water.     Waste Classification and Disposal:  The oily water mixture was disposed at Intergulf, located at 10020 Bayport Blvd, Pasadena, TX 77507, phone number (281) 474-4210. The used absorbent material was recycled at Nickco Recycling, located at 3363 FM 3042, Pittsburg, TX 75686, Phone number (903) 856-3522.    Additional Corrective Actions:  No corrective actions were taken as the spill was a result of a vehicular accident in which the SCRI driver was found not to be at fault.    If you have questions or need additional information, please do not hesitate to contact me at (713) 844-9600, ext. 1138.  Thank you for your assistance in this matter.
column169: No corrective actions were taken as the spill was a result of a vehicular accident in which the Sun Coast Resources driver was found not to be at fault.

column168: Gasoline tanker truck was making a delivery of gasoline to a gas station in Belleville Michigan. A motorist at the gas station ran through the safety barrier/cones and ran over the gasoline delivery hose. The driver shut off the delivery valves and put absorbents on the released product.: An estimated 88 gallons of gasoline was released from the damaged hose onto the concrete. The released gasoline reached the frozen storm drain on the gas station lot. Belleville FD, Belleville PD and Washtenaw Environmental Agency responded and monitored clean-up. Terra Environmental Company removed the liquid gasoline from the frozen storm drain catch basin.
column169: The driver of the tank truck marked the area of delivery with safety cones. The motorist that ran through the safety area and over the delivery hose never stopped, left the scene. A license plate number was acquired. Belleville PD is investigating.

column168: THE COMPANY DRIVER LOADED OFF-ROAD DIESEL INTO HIS TRUCK AND DROVE IT OVER ROADS TO THE CLIENT SITE ABOUT TWO MILES AWAY. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE CLIENT SITE THE GATE GUARD ALERTED THE DRIVER TO A LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE REAR OF THE VEHICLE. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED THROUGH THE GATE ABOUT 75 FEET WHERE HE STOPPED AND DEPLOYED SORBENT MATERIALS FROM HIS ONBOARD SPILL KIT. HE INSPECTED THE REAR OF THE VEHICLE AND NOTED THAT PIPE CAP ON THE DISCHARGE LINE HAD COME OFF IN TRANSIT AND DIESEL FUEL SEEPAGE WAS IN THE PIPE.    ROOT CAUSE: GRIT IN THE GUILLOTINE VALVE SEAT ALLOWED SEEPAGE TO PASS THE BLADE AND INTO THE DISCHARGE PIPE. THIS WAS CONTAINED FOR A PERIOD OF TIME BY THE PIPE DUST CAP. ROAD VIBRATION LOOSENED THE DUST CAP AND WHEN IT CAME OFF (AND DANGLED BY ITS RETENTION CABLE) IT RELEASED THE SEEPAGE ONTO THE ROADWAY WHILE THE VEHICLE WAS IN TRANSIT.
column169: THE EXISTING PISTON VALVE (GUILLOTINE STYLE) WAS CLEANED AND INSPECTED. GRIT WAS REMOVED FROM THE VALVE SEAT. THE VALVE WAS VISUALLY TESTED TO ENSURE IT LAID FLAT AGAINST THE JOINT AND THE VEHICLE RETURNED TO SERVICE WITH A NEW LOCKABLE DUST CAP. A MAINTENANCE PURCHASE ORDER WAS LET FOR A NVE PISTON GATE VALVE WITH CARBON STEEL BLADE AND VITON SEAL TO REPLACE THE EXISTING BETTS VALVE. THE VALVE WILL BE REPLACED WITH THE NVE WHEN IT ARRIVES.

column168: At the night of January the 2nd at approximately 11:30pm, the driver ARTEMIO CASTANEDA was on the Hauglum #1 H lease. While loading the driver heard the alarm sound informing him that 170 barrels were complete. Mr. Castaneda unhooked the auto override hose that is standard in our trucks. Mr. Castaneda got distracted and went into the truck to work with his handheld breaking the procedures of attending the truck while loading.When he realized the situation immediately shut down the pump and reported to the office. We tried unsuccessfully to contact the gauger therefore we could not inform the incident in a timely manner. Next morning we dispatched a cleanup crew to clean properly all the affected area. The cleanup crew removed all the contaminated soil from the ground and later was taken to dispose properly and level the terrain after that.

Hydrite blends and hauls products for Washing Systems to customers of Washing Systems.   A representative from Washing Systems typically meets the Hydrite drivers at Washing System customer facilities.      Hydrite’s driver, Rob Sauer, arrived at Cintas in Rockford, IL at 7:50 a.m. on 1/13/15 with Tanker LT1796 to deliver Advance, Structure, and Express from a 3 compartment trailer.  Mike Litrell of Washing Systems met Rob Sauer at the Cintas plant, and they discussed the product delivery amounts.   Mike told Rob that they could not off-load all of the Structure because there would not be enough room in the tank.   Mike also told Rob that the Express would go into 2 tanks and that they would start with Advance, then Structure, and end with Express.   By delivering in this order, which is non-hazardous to caustic, the same transfer hose could be used.    Rob unloaded the Advance first.  The air from blowing out the line was released through the receiving tank.    Rob then transferred all of the Structure except for approximately 100 gallons.  At that point, Rob shut the valve at the tanker and the storage tank.  Rob “walked the hose back” to the bleeder valve (Chicago fitting at the tanker discharge), which was set up to deposit residual material into a bucket.  Mike from Washing Systems disposed of this material in Cintas’ drain.    Lastly, Rob (wearing full PPE – suit, gloves, boots, goggles, and face shield) connected the hose to the Express compartment and on the other end connected to the smaller Express tank.  Rob transferred 550 gallons of Express to the small Express tank and closed the inlet valve to the small Express storage tank.   Rob then went to the tanker and shut the discharge valve at the tanker.     Rob and Mike discussed how to bleed off the pressure in the line.   Rob decided to run the excess into the storage tank.   Rob connected the air to the bleeder connection at the tanker discharge and opened the bleeder valve to blow out the line.   Rob walked back inside the Cintas plant.  Mike was located at the inlet valve to the small Express storage tank, and Mike told Rob that he had already opened and closed the inlet.  Mike told Rob that the line was empty and to switch the line to the other tank.     As a result, Rob went outside to move the air line from the bleeder to the tanker compartment.    Rob went inside to move the hose to the 2nd Express tank.   When Rob loosened  the second ear, the hose still had enough pressure that it blew off the connection and blew mist of the Express product to where Mike and Keith (Cintas) were standing – about 40 feet away.   Evidence of the material on the floor could be seen up to 50 feet away.   Mike and Keith were both exposed to this material but were not wearing full body PPE.  (Per Mike, Cintas does not require full body PPE if an employee is standing 20 feet away from the transfer site).   Mike was wearing safety glasses.    Mike and Rob helped Keith to a safety shower where Mike and
column169: The root cause of the incident was failure to adequately bleed the line (failure to follow our standard operating procedure TR013AF).   Although the driver has been trained on these procedures, and has successfully done this for years, this failure resulted in an injury.   That driver has been disciplined.    All drivers at the MK facility have been retrained on the need to bleed pressure.   The line could have been bled by disconnecting the air to the bleeder, and then using the bleeder valve to bleed the excess pressure.  Drivers who are actively unloading must physically verify that the line has been bled before it is disconnected.        In addition, the Cintas employee did not use an eyewash, and instead used Coca Cola, which is acidic.   Drivers were reminded that if they are involved in a bulk transfer, they must locate the nearest eyewash and safety shower in addition to wearing the required personal protective equipment.

column168: ON JANUARY 23RD, 2015, ACCESS USA RECEIVED AN INBOUND GROUND PACKAGE FROM UPS UNDER TRACKING NUMBER1ZR25A97A890802955 FROM ARAMEX SHOP AND SHIP ("SHOP & SHIP"), LOCATED AT 182-21 150TH AVENUE, SPRINGFIELD GARDENS, NEW YORK, USA, 11413.  SHOP & SHIP DESCRIBES ITSELF AS AN INTERNATIONAL SHIPPING SERVICE; IT OFFERS SIMILAR SERVICES TO THOSE PROVIDED BY ACCESS USA. UPS DELIVERED THE PACKAGE TO ACCESS USA AS AN UNREGULATED SHIPMENT. THE PACKAGE IS ADDRESSED TO ACCESSS USA CUSTOMER EMHEMED BESKARI IN SUITE NUMBER 027-552.  PRIOR TO OPENING THE PACKAGE, ACCESS USA EMPLOYEES NOTED THAT UN SPECIFICATION MARKING WERE VISIBLE ON THE PACKAGE AND THAT APPROXIMATELY EIGHT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MARKINGS AND LABELS HAD BEEN COVERED, AT LEAST IN PART. PLEASE SEE THE ATTACHMENT FOR PHOTOGRAPHS OF THE OUTSIDE OF THE PACKAGE AS IT LOOKED WHEN IT ARRIVED AT ACCESS USA'S WAREHOUSE. AN ORIGINAL UPS CROSSBORDER GROUND DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPPING PAPER (HAZARDOUS DECLARATION) AND UPS TDGR AUDIT CHECKLIST WERE IN THE OUTER POUCHES OF THE PACKAGE, BUT THE POUCHES HAD BEEN TAPED OVER AS IF TO CONCEAL THE DOCUMENTS.  THE HAZARDOUS DECLARATION CITED 1) UN3268, AIR BAG MODULES CLASS 9, PG III, EX 1993040309, 1 FIBERBOARD BOX, 5.40 KGS; AND 2) UN3268, SEAT-BELT PRETENSIONER CLASS 9, PG III, EX 1993040309, 1 FIBERBOARD BOX, 4.08 KGS.  WHEN ACCESS USA OPENED THE PACKAGE  PER ITS STANDARD PROCEDURES, THE PACKAGE DID , IN FACT CONTAIN TWO AIR BAG MODULES, TWO SEAT-BELT PRETENIONERS, AND ONE AIR BAG CONTROL UNIT.  PHOTOGRAPHS SHOWING THE CONTENTS OF THE PACKAGE ALSO ARE INCLUDED IN THE ATTACHMENT.  ACCESS USA HAS SPOKEN TO UPS REGARDING THIS SHIPMENT AND UNDERSTANDS THAT, BECAUSE THE MARKINGS AND LABELS HAD BEEN COVERED, UPS DID NOT REALIZE THAT IT WAS HANDLING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WHEN THE PACKAGE WAS DELIVERED TO ACCESS USA.  UPS HAS BEEN NOTIFIED THAT ACCESS USA IS FILING THIS REPORT, AND UPS HAD BEEN PROVIDED WITH A COPY OF THE SAME.  IT APPEARS THAT THIS PACKAGE ORIGINATED FROM LKQ PINTENDRE AUTOS INC FROM PINTENDRE, QC, CANADA UNDER UPS TRACKING NUMBER 1Z662F6E6860638662.  UPS CONFIRMED THAT SHOP & SHIP WAS NOT THE CONSIGNEE OF THE ORIGINAL PACKAGE, BUT THAT THE DESTINATION ADDRESS WAS AN ADDRESS GEOGRAPHICALLY CLOSE TO THE SHOP & SHIP OFFICE.  THUS,  IT MAY BE POSSIBLE THAT THE ORIGINAL CONSIGNEE BROUGHT THE PACKAGE TO THE SHOP & SHIP OFFICE.  UPON RECEIPT, ACCESS USA DECLINED THESE ITEMS FOR EXPORT AND IS NOW HOLDING THEM IN A SECURE PORTION THEM IN A SECURE PORTION OF ITS WAREHOUSE.

column168: THE DRIVER (MALCOLM) STATED HE APPROACHED THE STOP SIGN AT RIVER LANE, TAPPED HIS BREAKS, THAT IS THEN WHEN HE STATES HE FELT THE TRAILER SLIDE. THE TRUCK WAS AT A COMPLETE STOP. THE DRIVER STATES HE RELEASED  HIS SEATBELT, GOT HIS JACKET FROM THE PASSENGER SIDE SEAT, EXITED THE TRUCK, THEN CALLED HIS BOSS (ERICK). ERICK ASKED MALCOLM TO THEN TAKE A PICTURE OF THE TRUCK, UNSURE OF THE SITUATION. AS ERICK WAS OUT ON A LOAD HIMSELF. AT THIS MOMENT THE TRUCK WAS STILL UPRIGHT, YOU CAN SEE IN THE PHOTOS THAT THE TRUCK WAS SLIGHTLY AT AN ANGLE. MALCOLM WAS NOT IN THE TRUCK WHEN THE TRUCK CAME TO REST ON IT'S SIDE. WHEN THE TRUCK SLIDE OVER IT BENT OVER A STREET SIGN, WHICH THEREFORE RIPPED A SMALL GAP IN THE VAPOR RAIL. THE TRUCK COULD NOT BE MOVED UNTIL SOME OF THE FUEL HAD BEEN EXTRACTED, ONTO ANOTHER TRUCK. THE TRUCK WAS GROUNDED FOR SAFETY BEFORE ANY PROCEDURES WAS PERFORMED. DURING THAT PROCESS WAS WHEN THE 10 GALLON LOSS OCCURRED, THROUGH THE VAPOR RAIL. ABSORBENT PADS, AND BOOMS WAS PUT IN PLACE TO ABSORB THE GASOLINE, A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE VAPOR RAIL. AS SOON AS THE LEAK STARTED THE PROCESS OF EXTRACTING THE FUEL WAS STOPPED. THE TRUCK WAS THEN LIFTED BACK ONTO THE WHEELS, AND TRANSPORTED. AFTER THE TRUCK WAS REMOVED, CLEANUP STARTED IMMEDIATELY, AND ALSO DAYS AFTER. SOIL WAS REMOVED, REPLACED, AND SEEDED DISPOSED PROPERLY BY THE BOSLEY HAZMAT CLEANUP CREW.  SOIL SAMPLES WAS ALSO COLLECTED, AWAITING THE RESULTS.  WARREN TOWNSHIP VFD, STATE HIGHWAY PATROL, OHIO DOT, WAS ON SCENE.  GASOLINE WAS THE PRODUCT THAT WAS LEAKED FROM THE TRUCK. I HAVE ENCLOSED THE MSDS SHEETS FOR BOTH PRODUCTS THAT WAS ON TRUCK. THE COST OF THE CLEANUP IS UNKNOWN AT THIS TIME. WE ARE AWAITING A BILL.
